msgstr ""

#: /home/bee/code/godot/godot-docs-l10n/docs/classes/class_visualserver.rst:17
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: /home/bee/code/godot/godot-docs-l10n/docs/classes/class_visualserver.rst:19
msgid ""
"Server for anything visible. The visual server is the API backend for "
"everything visible. The whole scene system mounts on it to display."
msgstr ""

#: /home/bee/code/godot/godot-docs-l10n/docs/classes/class_visualserver.rst:21
msgid ""
"The visual server is completely opaque, the internals are entirely "
"implementation specific and cannot be accessed."
msgstr ""

#: /home/bee/code/godot/godot-docs-l10n/docs/classes/class_visualserver.rst:23
msgid "The visual server can be used to bypass the scene system entirely."
msgstr ""

#: /home/bee/code/godot/godot-docs-l10n/docs/classes/class_visualserver.rst:25
msgid "Resources are created using the ``*_create`` functions."
msgstr ""

#: /home/bee/code/godot/godot-docs-l10n/docs/classes/class_visualserver.rst:27
msgid ""
"All objects are drawn to a viewport. You can use the :ref:`Viewport "
"<class_Viewport>` attached to the :ref:`SceneTree <class_SceneTree>` or "
"you can create one yourself with :ref:`viewport_create "
"<class_VisualServer_method_viewport_create>`. When using a custom "
"scenario or canvas, the scenario or canvas needs to be attached to the "
"viewport using :ref:`viewport_set_scenario "
"<class_VisualServer_method_viewport_set_scenario>` or "
":ref:`viewport_attach_canvas "
"<class_VisualServer_method_viewport_attach_canvas>`."
msgstr ""

#: /home/bee/code/godot/godot-docs-l10n/docs/classes/class_visualserver.rst:29
msgid ""
"In 3D, all visual objects must be associated with a scenario. The "
"scenario is a visual representation of the world. If accessing the visual"
" server from a running game, the scenario can be accessed from the scene "
"tree from any :ref:`Spatial <class_Spatial>` node with "
":ref:`Spatial.get_world <class_Spatial_method_get_world>`. Otherwise, a "
"scenario can be created with :ref:`scenario_create "
"<class_VisualServer_method_scenario_create>`."
msgstr ""

#: /home/bee/code/godot/godot-docs-l10n/docs/classes/class_visualserver.rst:31
msgid "Similarly in 2D, a canvas is needed to draw all canvas items."
msgstr ""

#: /home/bee/code/godot/godot-docs-l10n/docs/classes/class_visualserver.rst:33
msgid ""
"In 3D, all visible objects are comprised of a resource and an instance. A"
" resource can be a mesh, a particle system, a light, or any other 3D "
"object. In order to be visible resources must be attached to an instance "
"using :ref:`instance_set_base "
"<class_VisualServer_method_instance_set_base>`. The instance must also be"
" attached to the scenario using :ref:`instance_set_scenario "
"<class_VisualServer_method_instance_set_scenario>` in order to be "
"visible."
msgstr ""

#: /home/bee/code/godot/godot-docs-l10n/docs/classes/class_visualserver.rst:35
msgid ""
"In 2D, all visible objects are some form of canvas item. In order to be "
"visible, a canvas item needs to be the child of a canvas attached to a "
"viewport, or it needs to be the child of another canvas item that is "
"eventually attached to the canvas."
msgstr ""

